WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
So, my name is Max. I am a physician from Washington, D.C.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.000
And what's happening right now is something that you guys are very familiar with.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:13.000
It's like, no, this code was working just a second ago. Hold, please.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
So, while we are figuring this out, we're going to do a thing

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
where I don't use slides and try to convince you

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
and simultaneously apologize for any transgressions

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
that clinicians have transgressed

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
during their interactions with you as data scientists.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
So, I live in three different worlds.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
The first world I live in is emergency medicine.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
And the specialty is largely what you think it is.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
It lives at the intersection of patients that really need care

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
and a system that doesn't.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
The other part of my life is critical care.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000
I practice cardiovascular surgical intensive care,

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:56.000
which means that nobody wants to come visit me at work.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Cardiovascular intensive care is a very quantitative field of medicine.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And you'd really hope that all medicine is quantitative,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.000
but you're about to figure out that it's really not.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And critical care led me to an interest in clinical research.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
And clinical research was kind of where my fun started.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Just checking in again. How are we doing?

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Aha!

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Let's go!

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
All right.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
So we talked about emergency medicine,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
intensive care, and clinical research.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And so my idea of clinical research when all of this started

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
was that I hand you this, right?

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And then I hand you an Excel file you put into the black box machine,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
which gives me a p-value.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And then we gallop into the sunset of PubMed.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.000
But what became even more clear, more quickly,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
is that what I'm actually handing you is something like this.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Some heinous spreadsheet that I thought was very well done.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
It turns out it's not.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And what the data scientist tells me is basically just kill it with fire.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
I never want to see this again.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And the project goes into the abyss.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
So you can pretty easily imagine that our first couple of doctor-scientist meetings,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I'm not sure who's who here, right?

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
And I was asking for things, and I wasn't really sure what I was asking for.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And so I sat with this for a long time.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
And when I went to grad school for clinical and translational research,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
I was having a lot of difficulty merging the gap

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
between health care professionals and data scientists.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And after sitting with this for a while,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
it hit me that health care communicates uncertainty.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
We love telling people what diseases they have.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Yes, you have coronary artery disease.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
No, you are negative for this.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And that is kind of how we're taught.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
And so in creating this kind of paradigm,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
I went back to kind of this book we have

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
that every medical student uses, this book called First Aid.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
And it's basically a high-yield board-review book.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And the year that I used this is, like, aggressively unimportant.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
But the point I want to make here

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
is that these two pages

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
are all doctors learn about biostats.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
So there's something about, like, incidence and prevalence.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Please don't try to read my handwriting.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
It's not useful to anyone's time.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And so really this is all we learn about numeracy, biostats, and inference.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And so this is then continued

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
and reinforced by the way that we take tests.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So, like, every test in medical school is the same.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
The question here is about a disease called Goodpasture syndrome.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Please don't look this up.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
But again, it all starts the same.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Patient comes in with a thing, and then we're given a set of data.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And then we have to do something really, really gnarly,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
which is dichotomize a continuous variable to say something is high or low.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
And then the question gives you some other, like,

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
aggressively unhelpful information.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And then you pick the answer choice, which here is A.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And this is something that we use all the time to address concern

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
for something called acute coronary syndrome or heart attack.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And I was working with a resident the other night,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
and I said, hey, is the troponin back? Can we, like, move on?

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:24.000
And he said, yeah, the troponin's back, and it's negative.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Right, and I see people over here, like, clutching their pearls.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Yes, right, correct.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Their idea of negative is binary plus minus

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
when our interpretation of that is, like,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
what's the limit of an assay of a continuous variable?

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Guaranteed that no doctor thinks about that.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And to reinforce our mistreatment of numbers,

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
this is a white blood cell count that we get part of a panel

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
called a complete blood count, or CBC.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
And you'll notice here that the normal high range is 10.8,

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
and the value here is 10.9.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Many people will say, ah, value 10.9 is higher than 10.8.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
This patient has a very high white blood cell count.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
We have no concept of what error is.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And when we hear about error, it's something that I did wrong,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
not necessarily a thing that happens.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And we can create a lot of cool diagrams like this, right?

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
So the incidence of a certain disease process over time

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
appears to be going down.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And this has, this is probably just, you know,

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
the disease getting better, right?

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
So rather than using causal inference,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
what doctors do is more casual inference,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
where we kind of see like, ah, that's going down,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
therefore the two must be related.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And you can imagine that this is like in direct confrontation

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
to our data science colleagues

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
who like to communicate in uncertainty,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
which is to say when they publish papers,

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
they say how uncertain they are.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
So this is a manuscript that was published a couple of years ago,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
just by way of its execution.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
The TLDR is patients that come to the hospital by ambulance

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
die more than those who don't come by ambulance.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Uh-huh.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So that's good.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
But when you look here,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
the confidence interval for this odds ratio

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
is between 7 and 17.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Is that a helpful number for anybody?

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
I would argue no.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And so I remember in grad school then learning

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.000
about bootstrap confidence interval,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
and we were about two hours into a lecture,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:41.000
and the professor's up there doing some like very mathy stuff

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
at the front of the room,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
and I remember in my post call, unfiltered state,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
saying like, what are we doing here?

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And that was meant more of like a meta,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
and so the professor said,

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
we're just seeing how big the error is.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
The estimate stays the same in all this foolishness

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
that we're doing up here on the board

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
is like for a confidence interval,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
and unfortunately clinicians don't understand

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
how important those error bars are.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So it's not necessarily surprising that a lot of clinicians

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
will look to the p-value or some other measure

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
that we publish greater than .05.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Time for subgroup analysis.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
But this disparity in communication is not unique

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
to the dynamic between physicians and data scientists.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Anybody know what this picture's from?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Bay of Pigs invasion,

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
which I know is not on the forefront of everybody's mind,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:44.000
but the reason that the Bay of Pigs invasion

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
was okayed by the U.S. government

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
was because there was a fair chance of success.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Now, in the report that was issued afterwards by the CIA,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
it turns out what was said in the room

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
was that the odds were 3 to 1,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
and unfortunately using this imprecise probabilistic language,

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
3 to 1, oh, that sounds good, let's go,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
which resulted in what is arguably

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
one of the larger military kerfuffles in world history.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So it's not surprising that experts are really good

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
at what they do, right?

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
They have knowledge, they have skill,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
and they've been really, really dedicated.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
What we are not taught anything about is communication,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
and so the solution to this

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
is actually partnership and nosiness.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So I want you to be nosy.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
The point of why I'm here today is I want you to get into

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
the nitty-gritty of the investigation that you're doing

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
because they're really, really different.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
So when I say be nosy, I mean I want you to ask,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
like, why are you doing this thing?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
How does that work? Why is that there?

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And in return, what really helps us is to hear, like,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
the reason I'm using Model A is because I don't like Model B.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
So when I say learn anatomy and physiology,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
A&P is like one of those bread-and-butter classes

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
that we do in medical school.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
In and out, any variation is bad, right?

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
That's, like, the first two years of medical school.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:17.000
And so a lot of what I do is hemodynamic research.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
So when I report heart pressures, feel free to ask,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
why do we care so much about pressure in the right atrium?

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
Well, really, it's because of the health

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
of the pulmonary vasculature.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Similarly, why are you using linear regression

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
as opposed to logistic regression?

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
Any data scientist that could possibly be asked.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
You'd be surprised the number of doctors that struggle

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
with when to use linear versus logistic regression.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
So similarly, in both fields, we have pathology.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Sometimes the heart does weird stuff,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
and we have to deal with it.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And sometimes in your IDE, it does weird stuff.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And similarly, we have diagnostics.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
When we have a question, we will do a CT scan,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
we will do a CT scan.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And similarly, when you have a problem with a model,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
you do nearly identical diagnostics

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
just using different words.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So when you see a CAT scan or results of a CAT scan,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
please feel free to ask us, why is this gray

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
and this is a little bit less gray?

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
In the same way, say, listen, the reason I'm not using

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.000
your really good idea is because the model doesn't work

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.000
as instrumental to our growth as clinicians

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
and as physician researchers that we learn this.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.000
And just like we have diagnostics, we have therapeutics.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
Sometimes when the heart is acting crazy,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
sometimes we apply electricity to get it back

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
in the correct rhythm.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
Similarly, when your data is acting a little bit crazy,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
you do something to it to make it act a little bit better.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
And so when I say to consider our IDEs,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I work where I used to work every day.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And so I want you to take a moment and look at every single

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
part of this room that could potentially give you

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
a piece of data.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
You have a ventilator in the back, you have an ultrasound,

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
you have a cardiac monitor, you have blood,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
but some of it stayed inside.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
But think about the amount of data that

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
healthcare professionals have to assimilate very, very quickly.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
This is our IDE.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
This is our other IDE.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So this is what's called a flow sheet.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And this is not a real patient.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
This is, like, I found it online somewhere.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Amy Fisher is not a real person.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And this is just a way for us to interact with the patient

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.000
by way of the computer.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And this is a way for us, as clinicians, that we will or won't perform

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
to make a lot of these numbers different.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
Now, compared to that, a different IDE,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
where a lot of the data that you use

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
and eventually operationalize is done

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
and now what I'm told is positron

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
and that I will be using it from here on out.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
But what we think of on the clinician side

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
is that our vision is that this is what you're doing

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.000
in the background.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
And this, to us, is very, very confusing.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
I did take, like, a couple minutes and I saw a line integral in there

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
somewhere from a class that I drank my way through in college.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
But our vision of statistics and data science

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
is nearly uniformly this,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
which makes it very intangible to a lot of clinicians.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And so an old joke in medicine is, you know,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
one view is no view.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
And so whenever we look at a data set

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
or we look at a paper, what we may see is this.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
When we add data science professionals to our interpretation,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
what we actually see is this.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And the old joke in medicine is,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
while I get one view, always get the lateral.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.000
And so with that, I want us to seek partnership

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
and nosiness together.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
Anytime that you work with a physician or any other clinician,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
please indulge the,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
I want to tell you about this model.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
I want to tell you how I transformed this variable.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
Let's program this together because I guarantee you

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
your clinician is more scared of you than you are of them.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
And with that, I want to...

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
I had this slide very, very quickly while I was sitting there

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
because I want to display that I have the cutest pets on the Internet.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
And I have Avon Barksdale here

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
and Koa Brown who are very good boys and girls

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
and are also my partners in nosiness.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And with that, thank you so much.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Thank you very much.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Quick question.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Were you always interested in statistical concepts in your medical education

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
or was there a pivot to this when you started research?

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
Undergrad, I was a math major.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And statistics was sort of treated like,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
almost like physics where like,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
no, those are like the applied math people, we don't talk to them.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
And so I guess I recognized the importance of statistics.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
I wanted no part of it

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
until I realized that statisticians are really, really expensive

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
and that sometimes doing your own very basic stats

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
is a lot cheaper and they hate you less.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Totally makes sense.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
One more question.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Could you comment on any statistical concept

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
or anything like that that you believe

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
that is very important for other clinicians to know

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
that they likely do not?

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Yeah, I think that the biggest sin

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.000
that clinicians commit is dichotomization

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
of a continuous variable.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
And I've harped on this a little bit.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.000
I mean, the 10 bar count of 10.8 is fine,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
but 10.9 is an emergency is absurd.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
We all say that and we all are nodding our heads here

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
because we've had this conversation just using different words.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
But there are many clinicians

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
that don't necessarily have the appreciation

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
of where the error bars are.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
That with every value that you sample,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
there is a distribution around it.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
I would tell clinicians that yes, I'm saying this,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
but there is a certain guardrail of safety around what I'm saying.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
What I'm saying is correct up until a certain number of limits.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
I would say that that's the concept

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
that clinicians struggle with

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
is the concept of error,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
not necessarily that they've committed one.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Great. Thank you so much.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Sure.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
Thank you.

